      "comment_id" : 109656717,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@hyperpallium the first thing, <code>String.equals</code> does internally, is a reference comparison, like <code>if(this == other) return true;</code>. Since <code>String</code> is <code>final</code>, even the simplest JVMs will be capable of inlining that code, not to speak of modern common implementations. So if the strings are identical (equal and interned), the early reference comparison doesn’t gain much and in all other cases, it doesn’t help at all, except for the scenario where both are <code>null</code>, perhaps."
    } ],
